reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars slick, compact, durable and functional
reviews.reviewText: This is my personal preference, but I like that the ports are only on one side and the end opposite the cord. This makes it much easier to manage the connection cords as they can lie flat and daisy chain them if even more than seven (7) total ports are needed. This device could make it very simple to create a Redundant Array of Inexpensive Devices (RAID) for a very secure backup.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 27, 2023
reviews.reviewText: Totally great. Due to its accessories, it fits any computer and any holes in it. It also can receive any USB, narrow or wide, since it got holes for them all. It is a great gadget, and half the price of other, sophisticated gadgets like this. The only thing I wished it had, is if it "clicked" when you attach it to the computer so that you know it is done right. It does not make that click sound when attaching it

reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Small but perfectly formed
reviews.reviewText: I bought this for my 13 year-old who had been nagging me for a USB hub for ages. The cool thing about this is that it can work with either a USB-A or USB-C host computer. This is perfect for him because he has an old hand-me-down laptop which does not have USB-C, but his next laptop definitely will have.On the hub there are two USB-C connectors one of which can be used to give the hub power, if you are using it on a USB-A host.This thing is so much smaller than I thought it would be, and it will be perfect for those who travel.
